at the Academy of American
Poets, and our pals

00:15:08.600 --> 00:15:09.900
in the Poetry Foundation.

00:15:09.900 --> 00:15:11.200
It's so great of
you to come here

00:15:11.200 --> 00:15:15.160
and launch these young poets
onto their year of service.

00:15:15.160 --> 00:15:18.530
As Kit mentioned, these
fine poets became eligible

00:15:18.530 --> 00:15:20.480
to be appointed as
national student poets

00:15:20.480 --> 00:15:22.810
because they first
received national awards

00:15:22.810 --> 00:15:24.890
through the Scholastic
Art and Writing Awards.

00:15:24.890 --> 00:15:28.420
The awards were started in 1923,
which is just about the time

00:15:28.420 --> 00:15:31.420
that the word teenager first
appeared in the dictionary.

00:15:31.420 --> 00:15:33.300
And our mission and
our purpose is

00:15:33.300 --> 00:15:35.570
to encourage creative
young people.

00:15:35.570 --> 00:15:38.670
So we have the privilege

00:15:38.670 --> 00:15:42.510
of launching these creative
young people onto their year

00:15:42.510 --> 00:15:45.850
of service and I wish all
of you could get to see some

00:15:45.850 --> 00:15:48.280
of them at work as I, I do.

00:15:48.280 --> 00:15:52.250
Last year on went on tour in
Idaho with Kinsell Houston

00:15:52.250 --> 00:15:55.730
who worked in a number
of different settings.

00:15:55.730 --> 00:15:58.450
She did a poetry
workshop for Doosan's,

00:15:58.450 --> 00:15:59.920
at the Boise Art Museum.

00:15:59.920 --> 00:16:01.570
She worked on an air
force base high school,

00:16:01.570 --> 00:16:04.300
and then she spent her
day at Boise High School

00:16:04.300 --> 00:16:05.620
where she read some
of her own work

00:16:05.620 --> 00:16:09.200
and advocates a creative
word cloud,

00:16:09.200 --> 00:16:11.220
and then write poems
about their homes.

00:16:11.220 --> 00:16:12.520
And when it came time to share,

00:16:12.520 --> 00:16:14.840
one of the students
raised their hand.

00:16:14.840 --> 00:16:16.210
And she was 15 years old.

00:16:16.210 --> 00:16:19.660
And started reading, I
remember my first home.

00:16:19.660 --> 00:16:20.960
And then you went -- she went

00:16:20.960 --> 00:16:24.650
on to artfully describe seven
more homes adding details

00:16:24.650 --> 00:16:29.040
about the light, the step
families that had come and gone.

00:16:29.040 --> 00:16:31.530
It was a stunning
moment, a pause.

00:16:31.530 --> 00:16:32.830
The class did this.

00:16:32.830 --> 00:16:34.130
[ Snapping fingers ]

00:16:34.130 --> 00:16:35.430
We do a lot of this

00:16:35.430 --> 00:16:36.730
in the Scholastic Art
and Writing Awards.

00:16:36.730 --> 00:16:38.630
And they moved on,
but I've reflected

00:16:38.630 --> 00:16:40.810
on that student quite a bit.

00:16:40.810 --> 00:16:45.050
Because she so aptly described
how poetry shortcuts the

00:16:45.050 --> 00:16:47.980
expression of complex
emotions and ideas.

00:16:47.980 --> 00:16:51.780
And how powerful it is, it
has the power to connect us,

00:16:51.780 --> 00:16:55.930
to explain, to provoke,
to express, to explore.

00:16:55.930 --> 00:16:59.060
It's very complicated being
a teenager these days.

00:16:59.060 --> 00:17:01.240
It always has been,
but especially now.

00:17:01.240 --> 00:17:06.210
What better past time could they
possibly grab on to than poetry

00:17:06.210 --> 00:17:08.710
and helping guide them
through the teenage years.

00:17:08.710 --> 00:17:10.950
These teen poets are
particularly well suited

00:17:10.950 --> 00:17:12.250
to advocate.

00:17:12.250 --> 00:17:14.330
They're young enough to be
relatable to little kids.

00:17:14.330 --> 00:17:17.170
And they're mature enough for
adults to take them seriously.

00:17:17.170 --> 00:17:21.040
The 2018 Class of National
Student Poets joins a legacy

00:17:21.040 --> 00:17:26.250
of incredible young writers
who feel poetry in their bones.

00:17:26.250 --> 00:17:29.420
And their voices are
strong and unique,

00:17:29.420 --> 00:17:31.750
and they will enter their year
of service fully committed

00:17:31.750 --> 00:17:36.460
to sharing their voices insights
and artistry to audiences large

00:17:36.460 --> 00:17:40.910
and small, grand and not so
grand, like those at the Library

00:17:40.910 --> 00:17:44.580
of Congress, and like
those at Boise High School.

00:17:44.580 --> 00:17:46.830
Poetry is an ancient
artform that continues

00:17:46.830 --> 00:17:52.040
to reinvent itself, and
make itself newly relevant,

00:17:52.040 --> 00:17:54.050
generation after generation.

00:17:54.050 --> 00:17:58.380
We are so proud to be here
to introduce you today

00:17:58.380 --> 00:18:01.530
to this generation's
finest young poets.

00:18:01.530 --> 00:18:04.170
So we have some wonderful
guests joining us here today.

00:18:04.170 --> 00:18:07.370
I want to thank all of you and
it's my honor now to welcome

00:18:07.370 --> 00:18:11.490
to the podium, New York Times
Op Ed Columnist David Brooks.

00:18:11.490 --> 00:18:12.790
There you go.

00:18:12.790 --> 00:18:14.590
Thank you so much.

00:18:14.590 --> 00:18:19.180
[ Applause ]

00:18:19.180 --> 00:18:20.800
&gt;&gt; David Brooks: So I was
talking to the students,

00:18:20.800 --> 00:18:23.170
the poets, earlier and
I mentioned when I was

00:18:23.170 --> 00:18:26.880
in college I applied for a --
to -- for a short story class.

00:18:26.880 --> 00:18:29.630
The professor thought it was
short story and poetry and so

00:18:29.630 --> 00:18:30.930
to get into the class we had

00:18:30.930 --> 00:18:34.240
to write a short story
and then also a poem.

00:18:34.240 --> 00:18:36.740
And I had never written
a poem before in my life.

00:18:36.740 --> 00:18:38.460
So I wrote the story
and I wrote the poem,

00:18:38.460 --> 00:18:42.190
and I wrote in the bottom,
I make no claims on poetry.

00:18:42.190 --> 00:18:44.420
And my professor
wrote, on the bottom,

00:18:44.420 --> 00:18:46.510
and it makes no claims on you.

00:18:46.510 --> 00:18:50.590
[ Laughter ]

00:18:50.590 --> 00:18:53.170
I, myself, do not have this gift

00:18:53.170 --> 00:18:56.980
but I'm the beneficiary
of poetry.

00:18:56.980 --> 00:19:00.170
And I'm the beneficiary
of the written word.

00:19:00.170 --> 00:19:02.570
And what I thought I'd do
just for a few minutes to try

00:19:02.570 --> 00:19:04.960
to illustrate what the
written word does for us.

00:19:04.960 --> 00:19:08.570
And so I have a home
ten blocks from here.

00:19:08.570 --> 00:19:11.360
And I have a collection
in that home.

00:19:11.360 --> 00:19:13.150
And some people collect stamps.

00:19:13.150 --> 00:19:16.410
I collect accounts of
different emotions.

00:19:16.410 --> 00:19:19.910
And so I collect
accounts of joy.

00:19:19.910 --> 00:19:22.730
And so for example, and when
you have all these accounts,

00:19:22.730 --> 00:19:24.900
you realize it comes in layers.

00:19:24.900 --> 00:19:27.920
There's physical joy that gets,
when people are moving together,

00:19:27.920 --> 00:19:30.850
my old history professor
was named Julio McNeal.

00:19:30.850 --> 00:19:33.270
And he was in bootcamp, and
he was marching with his men

00:19:33.270 --> 00:19:36.000
and he experienced
a moment of joy.

00:19:36.000 --> 00:19:38.980
He wrote, "Words are inadequate
to describe the emotion aroused

00:19:38.980 --> 00:19:42.710
by the prolonged movement in
unison that drilling involved.

00:19:42.710 --> 00:19:45.790
A sense of pervasive
well-being is what I recall.

00:19:45.790 --> 00:19:49.080
More specifically, a strange
sense of personal enlargement.

00:19:49.080 --> 00:19:50.380
A sort of swelling up.

00:19:50.380 --> 00:19:53.340
Becoming bigger than life,
thanks to participation

00:19:53.340 --> 00:19:55.000
in a collective ritual."

00:19:55.000 --> 00:19:57.100
And so that's one layer of joy.

00:19:57.100 --> 00:20:00.630
Another is what they call
collective effervescence.

00:20:00.630 --> 00:20:05.800
Every group of humanity dances
in rhythm when they're joyful.

00:20:05.800 --> 00:20:09.860
And so Zadie Smith was in
London in a nightclub in 1999,

00:20:09.860 --> 00:20:13.600
and she heard Q-Tip
rapping over the music.

00:20:13.600 --> 00:20:16.930
And she describes this moment.

00:20:16.930 --> 00:20:20.140
"A real thin man with enormous
eyes reached across the sea

00:20:20.140 --> 00:20:21.820
of bodies for my hand.

00:20:21.820 --> 00:20:24.870
He kept asking me the
same thing over and over.

00:20:24.870 --> 00:20:26.250
You feeling it?

00:20:26.250 --> 00:20:30.050
I was. My -- my ridiculous
heels were killing me.

00:20:30.050 --> 00:20:32.030
I was terrified I might die.

00:20:32.030 --> 00:20:35.140
Yet I felt simultaneously
overwhelmed with delight

00:20:35.140 --> 00:20:37.110
that can I kick it should
happen to be playing

00:20:37.110 --> 00:20:39.460
at this precise moment in
the history of the world.

00:20:39.460 --> 00:20:42.580
And was now morphing
into smells Latin spirit.

00:20:42.580 --> 00:20:46.660
I took the man's hand, the top
of my head flew away, we danced

00:20:46.660 --> 00:20:49.770
and danced, we gave
ourselves up to joy."

00:20:49.770 --> 00:20:51.330
That's another layer.

00:20:51.330 --> 00:20:52.960
Then there might be what
you call emotional joy.

00:20:52.960 --> 00:20:56.510
One of my heroes in life is
a woman named Dorothy Day.

00:20:56.510 --> 00:20:59.410
And she was -- got pregnant
and she realized that most

00:20:59.410 --> 00:21:01.950
of the accounts of childbirth
she'd ever read were written

00:21:01.950 --> 00:21:03.450
by men.

00:21:03.450 --> 00:21:05.890
So 45 minutes after giving
birth she wrote an account,

00:21:05.890 --> 00:21:07.190
a very beautiful account.

00:21:07.190 --> 00:21:09.530
And it ends with
a moment of joy.

00:21:09.530 --> 00:21:12.230
She writes, "If I had
written the greatest book,

00:21:12.230 --> 00:21:13.530
composed the greatest symphony,

00:21:13.530 --> 00:21:17.050
or carved the most exquisite
figure I could not have felt a

00:21:17.050 --> 00:21:18.690
more exalted creator than I did

00:21:18.690 --> 00:21:21.270
when they placed my
child in my arms.

00:21:21.270 --> 00:21:24.530
No human creature could receive
or contain so vast a flood

00:21:24.530 --> 00:21:28.650
of love and joy as I felt
after the birth of my child.

00:21:28.650 --> 00:21:33.030
And with this came the need
to worship and to adore."

00:21:33.030 --> 00:21:37.040
And when you see these moments,
you realize that joy happens

00:21:37.040 --> 00:21:39.930
when the skin barrier
between one person

00:21:39.930 --> 00:21:41.540
and another disappears.

00:21:41.540 --> 00:21:44.760
Joy often involves
a loss of self.

00:21:44.760 --> 00:21:47.490
David White who's a
-- a good poet writes,

00:21:47.490 --> 00:21:50.490
"Joy is a meeting place
of deep intentionality

00:21:50.490 --> 00:21:52.160
and self-forgetting.

00:21:52.160 --> 00:21:54.390
The bodily alchemy of
what lies inside us

00:21:54.390 --> 00:21:55.690
in communion would have

00:21:55.690 --> 00:22:00.000
but formerly seemed
outside, but now is neither.

00:22:00.000 --> 00:22:03.800
Dance, laughter, affection,
skin touching skin,

00:22:03.800 --> 00:22:07.960
singing in the car, music in the
kitchen, the quite irreplaceable

00:22:07.960 --> 00:22:11.000
and companionable
presence of a daughter.

00:22:11.000 --> 00:22:14.100
The sheer intoxicating beauty
of the world that inhabited us

00:22:14.100 --> 00:22:17.310
as an edge between what we
previously thought was us,

00:22:17.310 --> 00:22:19.810
and what was not us."

00:22:19.810 --> 00:22:21.370
Then there's a couple
higher levels.

00:22:21.370 --> 00:22:22.670
I'll just two more.

00:22:22.670 --> 00:22:24.980
And one is transcendent joy.

00:22:24.980 --> 00:22:28.050
When we think we're
reaching across some barrier

00:22:28.050 --> 00:22:30.030
that we can't really explain.

00:22:30.030 --> 00:22:31.330
So I am not a poet.

00:22:31.330 --> 00:22:32.900
I have a friend whose
an actual poet.

00:22:32.900 --> 00:22:36.630
And his name is Christian
Wyman, a very beautiful poet.

00:22:36.630 --> 00:22:38.490
And wherever -- when
you talk to Chris,

00:22:38.490 --> 00:22:39.790
he's lived in a lot of cities.

00:22:39.790 --> 00:22:42.610
And he always lived there
because there was a woman there.

00:22:42.610 --> 00:22:44.190
So like, he lived in Buffalo.

00:22:44.190 --> 00:22:45.490
Why'd you live in Buffalo?

00:22:45.490 --> 00:22:46.790
Oh I had a girlfriend there.

00:22:46.790 --> 00:22:48.210
And then where, you know,
why'd you live in Rochester?

00:22:48.210 --> 00:22:49.510
Oh a girlfriend there.

00:22:49.510 --> 00:22:50.810
And so he lived in Progue.

00:22:50.810 --> 00:22:53.730
He had a girlfriend there.

00:22:53.730 --> 00:22:55.480
And so one night he was
working on this poetry,

00:22:55.480 --> 00:22:57.750
or one morning, in the kitchen.

00:22:57.750 --> 00:23:00.490
And he was just at
the kitchen table.

00:23:00.490 --> 00:23:03.890
And a falcon landed on the
windowsill across the window.

00:23:03.890 --> 00:23:06.670
And it scanned out and
it didn't seem him.

00:23:06.670 --> 00:23:09.660
It just was scanning, like
two feet away from him.

00:23:09.660 --> 00:23:12.310
And his girlfriend
was taking a shower.

00:23:12.310 --> 00:23:15.210
So he went and got her and said
come out you got to see this.

00:23:15.210 --> 00:23:17.760
So she came out dripping, naked.

00:23:17.760 --> 00:23:21.100
And they're standing there just
with this falcon right there.

00:23:21.100 --> 00:23:24.570
And the falcon turns and
looks eyes with Wyman.

00:23:24.570 --> 00:23:30.250
And his girlfriend said,
wish for something.

00:23:30.250 --> 00:23:32.260
Take this moment,
wish for something.

00:23:32.260 --> 00:23:33.950
And he later wrote
about a poem --

00:23:33.950 --> 00:23:35.820
he wrote a poem about
the experience,

00:23:35.820 --> 00:23:38.590
and it includes this stanza.

00:23:38.590 --> 00:23:42.560
"And for a long moment I'm
still in, I wished and wished

00:23:42.560 --> 00:23:46.220
and wished and wished that
the moment would not end.

00:23:46.220 --> 00:23:49.050
And just like that it vanished."

00:23:49.050 --> 00:23:51.930
So that's that content that
people have with nature.

00:23:51.930 --> 00:23:53.840
And then finally the --
the part I'll end with,

00:23:53.840 --> 00:23:55.910
and I actually don't
have a passage with this.

00:23:55.910 --> 00:23:59.990
Is some people -- some moments
of joy are just transcendent,

00:23:59.990 --> 00:24:02.810
but moments, and then they
go away, like Wyman's.

00:24:02.810 --> 00:24:05.250
But some people for
them, joy is not a --

00:24:05.250 --> 00:24:08.400
an experience it's an outlook.

00:24:08.400 --> 00:24:11.070
It's something they bring
into the world every day.

00:24:11.070 --> 00:24:15.050
And it comes from the habitual
giving other people's delight.

00:24:15.050 --> 00:24:17.110
And it becomes their permanent
way of being in the world.

00:24:17.110 --> 00:24:20.620
I was at a luncheon
here a couple years ago,

00:24:20.620 --> 00:24:23.300
and I was seated next
to the Dahlia Lama.

00:24:23.300 --> 00:24:25.310
And the guy laughs for
no apparent reason.

00:24:25.310 --> 00:24:26.610
He just starts laughing.

00:24:26.610 --> 00:24:28.720
And you're sitting there,
and you want to be polite,

00:24:28.720 --> 00:24:31.540
so you laugh, and then
he laughs, and you laugh.

00:24:31.540 --> 00:24:33.370
And I had nothing
to say to the guy,

00:24:33.370 --> 00:24:35.400
because he was just so happy.

00:24:35.400 --> 00:24:40.610
And so I finally said -- he
had a canvas Dahlia Lama bag,

00:24:40.610 --> 00:24:42.020
so I said, you got
any candy in your bag?

00:24:42.020 --> 00:24:44.690
And so he starts pulling
out the stuff in the bag.

00:24:44.690 --> 00:24:46.690
It turns out to be everything
you get in the First-Class cabin

00:24:46.690 --> 00:24:50.880
of an international flight,
like a little razor, ear plugs.

00:24:50.880 --> 00:24:52.560
But he just radiates joy.

00:24:52.560 --> 00:24:55.810
And Kathy and I have a friend,
a very famous guy, Yo-Yo Ma.

00:24:55.810 --> 00:24:58.390
That guy just radiates joy.

00:24:58.390 --> 00:25:01.480
And that to me is a
higher form of life

00:25:01.480 --> 00:25:04.270
because they are just delight
in things, delight in gratitude

00:25:04.270 --> 00:25:05.820
and they offer goodness.

00:25:05.820 --> 00:25:08.150
Now so why have I
run through all this?

00:25:08.150 --> 00:25:09.450
It seems to me we're born

00:25:09.450 --> 00:25:11.180
with relatively primitive
understandings

00:25:11.180 --> 00:25:14.040
of our own emotions,
at least men are.

00:25:14.040 --> 00:25:16.060
[ Laughter ]

00:25:16.060 --> 00:25:18.290
But what language, and
especially poetry does,

00:25:18.290 --> 00:25:21.360
is it educates us
in our own emotions.

00:25:21.360 --> 00:25:24.100
When you've read a poem, you
haven't gotten new knowledge,

00:25:24.100 --> 00:25:27.570
or new information, but
you've had a new experience.

00:25:27.570 --> 00:25:30.530
And oft it's -- it's an
emotional experience.

00:25:30.530 --> 00:25:33.790
And you widen your
repertoire of emotions.

00:25:33.790 --> 00:25:37.150
The greatest poet of our day,
Taylor Swift, was once asked,

00:25:37.150 --> 00:25:40.210
I actually sort of mean that.

00:25:40.210 --> 00:25:42.950
Was once asked, you
write all about sadness.

00:25:42.950 --> 00:25:46.230
She says, there are actually
22 different kinds of sadness.

00:25:46.230 --> 00:25:48.510
There's your dog leaves sadness,
your boyfriend dumps you,

00:25:48.510 --> 00:25:50.900
your mom -- and she played a
different tune for all kinds.

00:25:50.900 --> 00:25:53.690
She's an expert on sadness.

00:25:53.690 --> 00:25:57.390
And so it's like we're born
with one piano key for joy.

00:25:57.390 --> 00:25:59.370
But through poetry and
through language we learn,

00:25:59.370 --> 00:26:02.320
well there are actually
88 different piano keys.

00:26:02.320 --> 00:26:04.270
And who would want to live
with the simplistic notion

00:26:04.270 --> 00:26:06.710
of our own emotions when you
can live with an enriched one.

00:26:06.710 --> 00:26:09.350
It's the sort of thing that
just makes life so much better.

00:26:09.350 --> 00:26:12.940
And then finally, if you
realize joy is the kind of thing

00:26:12.940 --> 00:26:17.150
that the Dahlia Lama or Yo-Yo
Ma could experience and project,

00:26:17.150 --> 00:26:19.400
why would you want to live
for just mere happiness

00:26:19.400 --> 00:26:20.700
when you could have joy?

00:26:20.700 --> 00:26:22.160
And when you make that kind

00:26:22.160 --> 00:26:24.410
of realization your whole
life can turn around.

00:26:24.410 --> 00:26:28.710
And so that's what I think
you guys are offering, the --

00:26:28.710 --> 00:26:31.550
the explication of
your own emotions

00:26:31.550 --> 00:26:34.790
and giving everybody a sense of
what you've learned about them.

00:26:34.790 --> 00:26:37.050
And so I congratulate you,

00:26:37.050 --> 00:26:39.090
I thank you for what
you're about to do.

00:26:39.090 --> 00:26:42.560
And as I mentioned, one
serious note, this is a moment

00:26:42.560 --> 00:26:46.450
where our nation needs
a story, and it needs

00:26:46.450 --> 00:26:48.610
to be told through poetry.

00:26:48.610 --> 00:26:52.250
And so I ask that you spend some
time at this next year filling

00:26:52.250 --> 00:26:55.050
in what is a gap and that if
there's anything that's going

00:26:55.050 --> 00:26:58.630
to unite such a diverse
country it's going to be poetry

00:26:58.630 --> 00:27:00.950
and story and narrative.

00:27:00.950 --> 00:27:03.900
And I'm -- I'm sure you're
going to play a role in that.

00:27:03.900 --> 00:27:05.340
So I have never experienced
the kind

00:27:05.340 --> 00:27:07.670
of joy that Sadie Smith did.

00:27:07.670 --> 00:27:10.120
I can't dance to Q-Tip.

00:27:10.120 --> 00:27:13.770
But I have had a couple
of experiences of joy

00:27:13.770 --> 00:27:17.000
and this is a replication of
one of my earlier experiences.

00:27:17.000 --> 00:27:19.560
Twice in my life I've
had this experience.

00:27:19.560 --> 00:27:21.030
Introducing Valerie June.

00:27:21.030 --> 00:27:23.040
[ Laughter ]

00:27:23.040 --> 00:27:24.460
And this is my second.

00:27:24.460 --> 00:27:25.820
And this is joy personified.

00:27:25.820 --> 00:27:27.620
Valerie.

00:27:27.620 --> 00:27:45.760
[ Applause ]

00:27:45.760 --> 00:27:48.950
&gt;&gt; Valerie June: Well
I have the pleasure

00:27:48.950 --> 00:27:52.440
of spending some personal
time with the students.

00:27:52.440 --> 00:27:59.040
And I was asking each one
of them about their voices.

00:27:59.040 --> 00:28:05.020
And I'm a musician but also a
songwriter, and a poet as well.

00:28:05.020 --> 00:28:09.190
So the voice of the poet is
really an interesting thing

00:28:09.190 --> 00:28:10.490
to me.

00:28:10.490 --> 00:28:13.530
And one thing they told me,
each one in their different way,

00:28:13.530 --> 00:28:14.930
of how they hear the voice

00:28:14.930 --> 00:28:20.100
of a poem is it usually
starts with one line.

00:28:20.100 --> 00:28:23.330
And I'll hear that line, and
I'll work with that line again

00:28:23.330 --> 00:28:25.260
and again for a little bit.

00:28:25.260 --> 00:28:27.110
And then I'll start
writing the poem.

00:28:27.110 --> 00:28:30.590
And the poems comes really fast
once they hear that one line.

00:28:30.590 --> 00:28:35.040
And they sit with it, then the
poem writing is fast after that.

00:28:35.040 --> 00:28:38.450
So I hope that you
go to your regions

00:28:38.450 --> 00:28:40.310
and you take those one lines,

00:28:40.310 --> 00:28:44.290
and you inspire everyone
in your region.

00:28:44.290 --> 00:28:46.520
And I know that you
have this power.

00:28:46.520 --> 00:28:48.270
I know you have the
power to do that.

00:28:48.270 --> 00:28:49.570
And it only takes but one line.

00:28:49.570 --> 00:28:54.080
I'm going to play a song
for you on my little baby,

00:28:54.080 --> 00:28:57.070
it's a song for love
and for healing.

00:28:57.070 --> 00:28:59.510
And it's called Somebody
to Love.

00:28:59.510 --> 00:29:04.040
[ Music ]

00:29:04.040 --> 00:29:09.970
Well if you're tired and
you're feeling so lonely,

00:29:09.970 --> 00:29:12.430
you wake up at night
and you thinking

00:29:12.430 --> 00:29:15.940
that only if you had somebody.

00:29:15.940 --> 00:29:17.240
Would I be somebody?

00:29:17.240 --> 00:29:20.500
Somebody to love.

00:29:20.500 --> 00:29:25.680
Did they tell you there were
