00:32:23.550 --> 00:32:28.510
And representing the
West is Ariana Smith.

00:32:28.510 --> 00:32:32.450
[ Applause ]

00:32:32.450 --> 00:32:36.000
I believe they're each
going to read something.

00:32:40.640 --> 00:32:41.940
&gt;&gt; Darius Atefat-Peckham:
Thank you all for coming.

00:32:41.940 --> 00:32:45.310
I'm the National Student Poet
representing the Midwest.

00:32:45.310 --> 00:32:46.960
I'm Darius Atefat-Peckham.

00:32:46.960 --> 00:32:49.960
I'm from Huntington, West
Virginia, and I go to school

00:32:49.960 --> 00:32:51.660
at Interlochen Arts Academy.

00:32:51.660 --> 00:32:55.990
This poem's called, the
Beautiful Day Dance.

00:32:55.990 --> 00:33:00.110
For my father, widower at 33.

00:33:00.110 --> 00:33:04.730
Mornings when I woke up
my face sagging, defeated,

00:33:04.730 --> 00:33:08.400
dad would smile at me and
wave his arms above his head.

00:33:08.400 --> 00:33:10.840
His legs kicking beneath him.

00:33:10.840 --> 00:33:13.200
A desperate flail,
but a chance to show

00:33:13.200 --> 00:33:16.210
that he could move his
body aw well as anyone.

00:33:16.210 --> 00:33:18.410
When the sunlight
seemed to break and spill

00:33:18.410 --> 00:33:21.630
down his raised chin like
egg whites, and the chill bit

00:33:21.630 --> 00:33:25.630
into us both, he'd sing.

00:33:25.630 --> 00:33:27.360
The song isn't as
important to me now

00:33:27.360 --> 00:33:28.860
as the beauty of the dance.

00:33:28.860 --> 00:33:31.450
And I'm sure the melody
was a repetitious rip off

00:33:31.450 --> 00:33:32.840
of zip-a-dee-doo-dah,

00:33:32.840 --> 00:33:35.660
though sometimes we tilted
our heads beneath the sky

00:33:35.660 --> 00:33:37.270
and just yelled it.

00:33:37.270 --> 00:33:38.650
Despite the neighbors.

00:33:38.650 --> 00:33:41.230
Dispelling puffs of
warm air from our mouths

00:33:41.230 --> 00:33:44.050
as we screamed, it's
a beautiful day.

00:33:44.050 --> 00:33:47.630
To the blue that filled the
space behind the clouds.

00:33:47.630 --> 00:33:49.700
To whoever was listening.

00:33:49.700 --> 00:33:51.540
To the way I sweat at nights.

00:33:51.540 --> 00:33:54.980
Dad rubbing the wet t-shirt that
clung to my back whispering,

00:33:54.980 --> 00:33:59.490
it's all right, we're OK,
over and over like a chorus.

00:33:59.490 --> 00:34:01.670
To the broken limbs
and the deaths

00:34:01.670 --> 00:34:04.230
that rendered us for a time.

00:34:04.230 --> 00:34:05.530
Living memories.

00:34:05.530 --> 00:34:06.830
Regretfully alive.

00:34:06.830 --> 00:34:10.120
But thankful that we could
always spin ourselves around,

00:34:10.120 --> 00:34:13.610
arms spread wide,
to live and dance

00:34:13.610 --> 00:34:16.130
and to sing anyways,
to sing always.

00:34:16.130 --> 00:34:17.930
Thank you.

00:34:17.930 --> 00:34:40.170
[ Applause ]

00:34:40.170 --> 00:34:41.470
&gt;&gt; Daniel Blokh: Shalom y'all.

00:34:41.470 --> 00:34:44.620
I'm Daniel Blokh.

00:34:44.620 --> 00:34:47.290
And I'm the Southeast
National Student Poet,

00:34:47.290 --> 00:34:48.920
if you wouldn't tell
from the all.

00:34:48.920 --> 00:34:54.340
I'm from Birmingham, Alabama
and my poem is called Sixty.

00:34:54.340 --> 00:35:00.220
Like his own father before him,
at 3:00 a.m. my father wakes,

00:35:00.220 --> 00:35:01.520
wanders the house a little,

00:35:01.520 --> 00:35:04.540
pours his cereal,
no eggs, no bacon.

00:35:04.540 --> 00:35:07.160
My father doesn't touch meat.

00:35:07.160 --> 00:35:11.240
Lives softly enough to enter
and leave the world a shadow,

00:35:11.240 --> 00:35:13.210
a breeze on doorsteps.

00:35:13.210 --> 00:35:15.450
He reads the news until I wake.

00:35:15.450 --> 00:35:17.510
On the way to school he'll talk

00:35:17.510 --> 00:35:20.500
about the latest friend
I didn't get to meet.

00:35:20.500 --> 00:35:24.860
This one was only 52 and
lived back in Kharkov.

00:35:24.860 --> 00:35:26.680
Each night they fleshed
their throats

00:35:26.680 --> 00:35:28.920
out let evening make
meat of them.

00:35:28.920 --> 00:35:31.850
It took years to
learn the way a body

00:35:31.850 --> 00:35:35.960
like a hurt dog holds its
history and tight jaws.

00:35:35.960 --> 00:35:38.460
My father shouts
at the car swerving

00:35:38.460 --> 00:35:40.120
in its lane ahead of us.

00:35:40.120 --> 00:35:43.300
Then asks, have you
reconsidered being vegetarian?

00:35:43.300 --> 00:35:44.720
I say, maybe.

00:35:44.720 --> 00:35:47.300
Which we both know
means, I don't want to go

00:35:47.300 --> 00:35:49.010
to the trouble of saying no.

00:35:49.010 --> 00:35:50.640
And we've pulled
up to the school.

00:35:50.640 --> 00:35:53.440
He hasn't had a chance
to talk about the news

00:35:53.440 --> 00:35:57.190
or say how proud he was to
watch another morning swell

00:35:57.190 --> 00:35:58.880
up through the cracks of night.

00:35:58.880 --> 00:36:02.320
I haven't had a chance to
wish him happy birthday,

00:36:02.320 --> 00:36:06.320
and anyway what is there
to say but good bye my son

00:36:06.320 --> 00:36:11.020
and good-bye father
who is my son.

00:36:11.020 --> 00:36:13.960
Whose eyes I carry into
any rearview mirror.

00:36:13.960 --> 00:36:15.770
Any 3:00 a.m. drive home

00:36:15.770 --> 00:36:19.240
when one car sideswipes
another behind me.

00:36:19.240 --> 00:36:23.300
My father, who knows we
live in worlds of wheels,

00:36:23.300 --> 00:36:25.460
all trying to catch us.

00:36:25.460 --> 00:36:27.260
Thank you.

00:36:27.260 --> 00:36:49.100
[ Applause ]

00:36:49.100 --> 00:36:50.400
&gt;&gt; Alexandra
Contreras-Montesano: Hello,

00:36:50.400 --> 00:36:52.110
my name is Alexandra
Contreras-Montesano.

00:36:52.110 --> 00:36:54.950
And I am representing
the Northeast.

00:36:54.950 --> 00:36:56.630
I'm from Burlington, Vermont,

00:36:56.630 --> 00:36:58.830
and I go to Burlington
High School.

00:36:58.830 --> 00:37:01.380
This is Puebla.

00:37:02.860 --> 00:37:07.710
Puebla is chocolate
dipped, syrupy as I spoon it

00:37:07.710 --> 00:37:11.020
out of the close-knit town
surrounding Mexico City.

00:37:11.020 --> 00:37:16.040
I just want to gulp it down,
suck the marrow from the cattle

00:37:16.040 --> 00:37:18.640
that get leaner every year.

00:37:18.640 --> 00:37:21.410
It smells good, being home,

00:37:21.410 --> 00:37:24.750
or being in a place
that was once home.

00:37:24.750 --> 00:37:28.610
I can't help but hold my
breath, abducting it in my lungs

00:37:28.610 --> 00:37:32.110
because the wind here
is a different flavor

00:37:32.110 --> 00:37:33.860
than the wind there.

00:37:33.860 --> 00:37:39.270
I thought the thing I missed
most was the sizzle your bare

00:37:39.270 --> 00:37:42.190
feet make against the packed
dirt of the evening road,

00:37:42.190 --> 00:37:46.350
but I was wrong because
I am intoxicated

00:37:46.350 --> 00:37:50.330
by the way my grandmother
clasps her hands to my heart.

00:37:50.330 --> 00:37:52.810
Like I never left.

00:37:52.810 --> 00:37:57.260
Puebla tastes salty, as I
like it from my top lip,

00:37:57.260 --> 00:37:59.350
brushing it from the
corners of my eyes,

00:37:59.350 --> 00:38:03.610
letting it fall,
absorb into my skin.

00:38:03.610 --> 00:38:07.690
I know I can't come back until
the next thunderstorm season.

00:38:07.690 --> 00:38:11.990
It gets easier to come
and harder to leave.

00:38:11.990 --> 00:38:15.780
I wish I could stay in this
town where everything tastes

00:38:15.780 --> 00:38:20.290
like cayenne mixed with just
the right amount of lime.

00:38:20.290 --> 00:38:23.050
It burns but you
laugh until the sour.

00:38:23.050 --> 00:38:24.850
Thank you.

00:38:24.850 --> 00:38:52.040
[ Applause ]

00:38:52.040 --> 00:38:55.150
&gt;&gt; Heather Laurel Jensen: Howdy.

00:38:55.150 --> 00:38:56.870
I'm Heather Laurel Jensen.

00:38:56.870 --> 00:38:58.310
I'm from Mesa, Arizona.

00:38:58.310 --> 00:39:00.700
I'll be representing
the Southwest.

00:39:00.700 --> 00:39:04.490
This is Allergy Apologizing
in Hindsight.

00:39:06.230 --> 00:39:11.380
I hear July will bring
the coming monsoon season

00:39:11.380 --> 00:39:14.210
and a stock market crash.

00:39:14.210 --> 00:39:17.900
Each light on the water tower
will blink and then strobe.

00:39:17.900 --> 00:39:22.900
A cougar will sleep under
my trampoline for weeks.

00:39:22.900 --> 00:39:25.460
Dogs will break into
every antique shop

00:39:25.460 --> 00:39:28.010
and devour fine china.

00:39:28.010 --> 00:39:31.610
From there the moon will
roll across the cliff

00:39:31.610 --> 00:39:34.890
and crush the nearest
mobile home.

00:39:34.890 --> 00:39:40.390
Today they are dredging my best
friend's body from the lake.

00:39:40.390 --> 00:39:44.540
She is wrapped in pink tarp, and
identifiable by her pony tail.

00:39:44.540 --> 00:39:47.860
The edges of each day
are okra and pulling

00:39:47.860 --> 00:39:49.660
up by the corners like linoleum.

00:39:49.660 --> 00:39:52.240
Occasionally when I take a
shower there is vomit already

00:39:52.240 --> 00:39:53.540
in the bathtub.

00:39:53.540 --> 00:39:54.840
I should not be here.

00:39:54.840 --> 00:39:56.320
Not like this.

00:39:56.320 --> 00:39:59.440
Three weeks ago we were kneeling
at the gulf of a psych ward

00:39:59.440 --> 00:40:02.260
with my hands pressing and
ziplocked to her nose and mouth

00:40:02.260 --> 00:40:04.610
in lieu of a paper bag.

00:40:04.610 --> 00:40:11.200
In hindsight, I am not even an
effective attempt at a solution.

00:40:11.200 --> 00:40:14.620
A threat is still a threat so
when you pretend it's benign.

00:40:14.620 --> 00:40:17.220
Sorrow is still sorrow
with my headphones in.

00:40:17.220 --> 00:40:19.690
Her grief was still
grief when I avoided it.

00:40:19.690 --> 00:40:25.360
In the future I hope to be
unafraid of asking questions.

00:40:25.360 --> 00:40:28.370
Her parents will join a nunnery.

00:40:28.370 --> 00:40:32.570
The lake will drain through
a metal slit in the earth.

00:40:32.570 --> 00:40:37.610
Her old things will appear
on every subway in the world.

00:40:37.610 --> 00:40:41.480
In hindsight, I will
look for the cliff crumbs

00:40:41.480 --> 00:40:44.290
in the cuffs of her jeans.

00:40:44.290 --> 00:40:50.510
In hindsight, I will call the
hospital and tell them her name.

00:40:50.510 --> 00:41:13.050
[ Applause ]

00:41:13.050 --> 00:41:14.660
&gt;&gt; Ariana Smith: Hey.

00:41:14.660 --> 00:41:18.200
OK. My name is Ariana Smith.

00:41:18.200 --> 00:41:19.880
I am from Las Vegas, Nevada,

00:41:19.880 --> 00:41:22.880
and I will be representing
the West region.

00:41:22.880 --> 00:41:26.570
This poem is entitled
Descendant.

00:41:26.570 --> 00:41:30.220
Grandfather, birthed from
burning crosses in dense

00:41:30.220 --> 00:41:33.810
and sticky Georgia, smoke
clinging to black skin

00:41:33.810 --> 00:41:36.540
like fresh cotton
to nimble fingers.

00:41:36.540 --> 00:41:39.010
Breathing in freedom
with zephyr.

00:41:39.010 --> 00:41:42.920
Sunday shoes stuck
in rich wet moss.

00:41:42.920 --> 00:41:46.090
Grandmother, blooming
out of rose milk week

00:41:46.090 --> 00:41:48.910
from the Carolinas,
twig like brown legs,

00:41:48.910 --> 00:41:51.500
skipping across sweeping
willows.

00:41:51.500 --> 00:41:54.330
Her clouds were frothy
and pastel.

00:41:54.330 --> 00:41:58.440
Pearlescent velvet swaying
like tiny dancers above her.

00:41:58.440 --> 00:42:02.830
Father, product of an
exodus from South to North,

00:42:02.830 --> 00:42:05.530
the other side of the sunshine.

00:42:05.530 --> 00:42:07.870
My father, a lingering love,

00:42:07.870 --> 00:42:11.720
weaved from ancestral
needle and thread.

00:42:11.720 --> 00:42:14.260
Blood line like a river, flowing

00:42:14.260 --> 00:42:18.900
through state line Mississippi
currents of dripping peach vine.

00:42:18.900 --> 00:42:22.410
I descend from the other
side of the train tracks,

00:42:22.410 --> 00:42:25.700
resembling country
border from suctioned lips

00:42:25.700 --> 00:42:27.910
to rattling jazz
trumpet measures,

00:42:27.910 --> 00:42:31.580
from hot buttery biscuits
on the kitchen stove.

00:42:31.580 --> 00:42:34.850
From mommas and aunties
with kaleidoscopes for eyes

00:42:34.850 --> 00:42:37.940
and the Freedom Riders
Bus set aflame in a city

00:42:37.940 --> 00:42:40.160
that was already burning.

00:42:40.160 --> 00:42:44.280
An eternity of southern
acrimony, a forbidden home,

00:42:44.280 --> 00:42:47.430
familiar, familial,
a fresh wound

00:42:47.430 --> 00:42:50.110
that never seems to scab over.

00:42:50.110 --> 00:42:55.790
There lay heritage,
blood, spirit, bone.

00:42:55.790 --> 00:42:58.900
Generations gone with the
wind, surviving through me,

00:42:58.900 --> 00:43:01.790
my heart strung to
theirs like DNA.

00:43:01.790 --> 00:43:04.580
Their flesh dissolving
like sugar cube,

00:43:04.580 --> 00:43:07.730
my body still on stolen land.

00:43:07.730 --> 00:43:10.350
Someday we will all
taste liberation

00:43:10.350 --> 00:43:13.510
on the tips of our tongues.

00:43:13.510 --> 00:43:35.010
[ Applause ]

