Better yet, we skipped
school to travel together.

00:44:43.030 --> 00:44:45.040
[ Laughter ]

00:44:45.040 --> 00:44:47.550
To New York City in October,
the Aspen Ideas Festival

00:44:47.550 --> 00:44:50.050
and Carnegie Hall in June.

00:44:50.050 --> 00:44:54.150
We were certainly the recipients
of a lot of generosity.

00:44:54.150 --> 00:44:57.880
People like Juan Felipe
Herrera, Dr. Katheryn Matthew,

00:44:57.880 --> 00:45:02.130
Dr. Carla Hayden, Sarah Jessica
Parker, Elizabeth Alexander,

00:45:02.130 --> 00:45:06.180
and Edward Hirsh lent us their
time and wisdom unreservedly.

00:45:06.180 --> 00:45:08.740
Thanks to the hard work of
the staff at the Alliance

00:45:08.740 --> 00:45:12.050
for Young Artists and Writers,
we've experienced affirmation

00:45:12.050 --> 00:45:15.580
and received a platform to
share poetry with our peers.

00:45:15.580 --> 00:45:18.000
We were given the
space to write bravely

00:45:18.000 --> 00:45:20.430
and delve deeply into poetry.

00:45:20.430 --> 00:45:23.730
But this year isn't about the
amazing gift each national

00:45:23.730 --> 00:45:26.090
student poet here
has been given.

00:45:26.090 --> 00:45:27.390
Don't get me wrong.

00:45:27.390 --> 00:45:30.100
We should say thank you
often and sincerely.

00:45:30.100 --> 00:45:33.130
After all, this program
is the culmination

00:45:33.130 --> 00:45:36.470
of many wonderful people's
vision and hard work.

00:45:36.470 --> 00:45:40.040
To Virginia, Hannah, Deborah,
Olivia and all the others

00:45:40.040 --> 00:45:43.120
who helped at the Alliance
and IMLS, we thank you

00:45:43.120 --> 00:45:45.430
from the bottom of our hearts.

00:45:45.430 --> 00:45:48.170
In eighth grade, my English
teacher asked our class

00:45:48.170 --> 00:45:51.090
to write essays not about
the best gift we got

00:45:51.090 --> 00:45:55.710
over winter break, but instead
about the best gift we gave.

00:45:55.710 --> 00:46:00.040
It shifted our perspectives to
generosity and thoughtfulness.

00:46:00.040 --> 00:46:02.650
And it was a lesson
that stayed with me.

00:46:02.650 --> 00:46:05.640
I share this with you because
at its heart this is the magic

00:46:05.640 --> 00:46:07.870
of the National Student
Poet's Program.

00:46:07.870 --> 00:46:11.430
They help us and we turn
around to help others.

00:46:11.430 --> 00:46:14.830
I know the Class of 2018 will
change their communities,

00:46:14.830 --> 00:46:17.930
amplify the voices too
often left unheard.

00:46:17.930 --> 00:46:21.650
Make more room at the table
for new and bright poets.

00:46:21.650 --> 00:46:25.050
I know this because each of
you is an astounding writer

00:46:25.050 --> 00:46:27.290
and ambassador to your craft.

00:46:27.290 --> 00:46:30.290
I also know this because
I've seen the same generosity

00:46:30.290 --> 00:46:35.210
in my friends, Ben, Kensal,
Juliette and Camilla this year.

00:46:35.210 --> 00:46:37.890
Camilla spent time helping
teach poetry therapy

00:46:37.890 --> 00:46:40.770
to immigrant advocates and
attorneys and connected

00:46:40.770 --> 00:46:43.960
with refugees from
Somalia and the Congo.

00:46:43.960 --> 00:46:46.460
Juliette collaborated
with doctors and patients,

00:46:46.460 --> 00:46:50.680
using language to heal
emotional trauma in hospitals.

00:46:50.680 --> 00:46:52.760
Kensal spent time
with Native students

00:46:52.760 --> 00:46:56.010
at the Sherman Indian Boarding
School discussing identity

00:46:56.010 --> 00:46:57.560
and the notion of home

00:46:57.560 --> 00:47:00.440
and published a collection
of their writings.

00:47:00.440 --> 00:47:02.680
Ben was poet and resident
for summer school,

00:47:02.680 --> 00:47:04.080
giving academic enrichment

00:47:04.080 --> 00:47:06.890
to local Minneapolis
middle schoolers.

00:47:06.890 --> 00:47:08.680
They've all accomplished
wonderful things

00:47:08.680 --> 00:47:11.000
and I hope you'll take
inspiration and guidance

00:47:11.000 --> 00:47:14.200
from them as you search
for your own path forward.

00:47:14.200 --> 00:47:17.050
Before we go, we of the
Class of 2017 wanted

00:47:17.050 --> 00:47:19.890
to give a few pieces of advice.

00:47:19.890 --> 00:47:21.270
Juliette says you should learn

00:47:21.270 --> 00:47:23.980
from everyone you
meet, and I agree.

00:47:23.980 --> 00:47:25.800
Ben urges you to be unafraid

00:47:25.800 --> 00:47:29.200
to seize the opportunity
you worked so hard for.

00:47:29.200 --> 00:47:31.590
We also recommend you
wear powder foundation

00:47:31.590 --> 00:47:33.010
in TV interviews.

00:47:33.010 --> 00:47:34.310
[ Laughter ]

00:47:34.310 --> 00:47:36.070
And send thank you notes early.

00:47:36.070 --> 00:47:39.000
Above all though, take a
lesson from Juan Felipe Herrera

00:47:39.000 --> 00:47:42.260
who spent the last 15 minute
of our master class together,

00:47:42.260 --> 00:47:44.330
showing us how to
fold Starbucks bags

00:47:44.330 --> 00:47:46.870
into makeshift poetry booklets.

00:47:46.870 --> 00:47:48.880
Looking back, I realize
he was showing us how

00:47:48.880 --> 00:47:51.190
to make room for poetry.

00:47:51.190 --> 00:47:54.280
And above all, remember you're
here because you earned it,

00:47:54.280 --> 00:47:57.920
and we need your voices
now more than ever.

00:47:57.920 --> 00:48:00.510
We're standing right beside
you, and we can't wait

00:48:00.510 --> 00:48:01.810
to see what you'll do.

00:48:01.810 --> 00:48:03.610
Thank you.

00:48:03.610 --> 00:48:14.040
